tyards. Theorizing the Medina by the Bay as a microcosm of socioeconomic, demographic, and political transformations in the twentieth- and twenty-first centuries, Kashani resituates Islam as liberatory and abolitionist theory, theology, and praxis for all those engaged in struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity lifezCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 0aCultural pluralismzCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 0aIntercultural communicationzCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 0aMinoritieszCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 0aMuslimsxSocial conditionszCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 0aMuslimszCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay Area. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027232?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027232/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles